    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-relative-speeds-of-objects-moving-in-different-directions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
        <title>Relative Speeds of Objects Moving in Different Directions</title>
        <objectives component="outcomes">
            <introduction xml:id="auto_ehcvtz6n">
                <dl>
                    <li xml:id="auto_dsh704f2">
                        <title>Strand</title>
                        <p xml:id="auto_cibkl6zl">
                            2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_x1tvvs21">
                        <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                        <p xml:id="auto_emuiszy9">
                            2.10 Linear Motion
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_s8vxxzg4">
                        <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                        <p xml:id="auto_2ye4gg2k">
                            Determine relative speed of two moving bodies in different situations.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_0u10706w" component="lesson-plan">
                        <title>Grade Level</title>
                        <p xml:id="auto_6zi62kge">
                            10
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ikjme2sr" component="lesson-plan">
                        <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                        <p xml:id="auto_rapiy0fo">
                            40 minutes
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </dl>
                <p xml:id="auto_42m01f2e" component="lesson-plan">
                    <p xml:id="auto_zllvsmes"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                    <ol>
                        <li xml:id="auto_0tkxy9sy">
                            <p xml:id="auto_bucfc683">
                                <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> When two objects move toward each other (in different directions), their relative speed is the sum of their individual speeds. Objects moving toward each other close the gap faster than objects moving in the same direction.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_ui17rcdn">
                            <p xml:id="auto_pbmna2mm">
                                <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate relative speed for objects moving in different directions. Use <m>\text{Time} = \frac{\text{Distance}}{\text{Relative Speed}}</m> to determine when objects meet.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_459g9afd">
                            <p xml:id="auto_if849w6m">
                                <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world problems involving trains, vehicles, and cyclists moving toward each other, including problems with different departure times.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                    </p>
                </p>
            </introduction>
        </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
            <!-- Link to blurb -->
            <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

            <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
                <sidebyside>
                    <p xml:id="auto_46ho13xw">
                        <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/linear-motion/relative-speeds-of-objects-moving-in-different-directions.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_zcnlr96f">
                        <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/linear-motion/step-by-step-guide_relative-speeds-of-objects-moving-in-different-directions.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                    </p>
                </sidebyside>
            </sbsgroup>
        </axiom>
        <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery (15 minutes)</title>
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_pgizh9ed">
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_s4u8i9pg">
                        15 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_29z88cj2">
                    <title>Grouping</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_gm2um3j5">
                        Work in small groups (3<ndash/>4 students)
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ub1odnxz">
                    <title>Materials</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_yifh73v8">
                        Toy car (pulled by string), string, stopwatch, measuring tape (10 metres), pen and paper, calculator
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_9dhypw89">
                    <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_unb1t2ke">
                        Circulate among groups, ensuring safe movement. This activity builds on the previous same-direction race — emphasise the key change: participants now move <em>toward each other</em>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p xml:id="auto_w6ochtuk">
                <alert>Facilitation Strategy:</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_pi9gka7n">
                <ul>
                    <li xml:id="auto_4qkswx72">Connect to the previous lesson: <q>Last time you raced in the same direction. What do you think happens to the relative speed when they move toward each other?</q></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_zx45ikgq">Ensure participants start at opposite ends of the measured distance.</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_uxzm5fku">Prompt: <q>Did they close the gap faster than when moving in the same direction? Why?</q></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_t0mw05pr">After the race, ask groups to compare their relative speed (sum) with the same-direction result (difference).</li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_y8p6afer">
                <alert>Discussion Prompts (after group work):</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_938mez99">
                <ul>
                    <li xml:id="auto_csrz3cuh">Who moved faster? Was the student walking faster or slower than the toy car?</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_jkhpx51s">How does this relative speed compare with the same-direction case?</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_l4k7ebdt">Why do we add speeds when objects move toward each other?</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_u2rk5w79">What would happen if both objects were moving at the same speed toward each other?</li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </axiom>


        <activity xml:id="auto_o603o8rx">
            <p xml:id="auto_vwydec5z">
                Using <term>Activity 2.9.7.</term> above now try the race such that the racers move towards each other.
                <ol xml:id="auto_4xlw7d2r" marker="(a).">
                    <li xml:id="auto_ewcnryba">
                        <p xml:id="auto_qnayzbx1">
                            Using the starting and finishing point.
                            <ul xml:id="auto_jeebs363">
                                <li xml:id="auto_6dq00wvs">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_btpjh1lo">
                                        Put the Student on the marked end, and
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_az49c7rj">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_szmh5l1x">
                                        The Toy car on the other end.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li xml:id="auto_aukg5me9">
                        <p xml:id="auto_1df31wdo">
                            Measure time, record and calculate the speeds.
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li xml:id="auto_hivzlods">
                        <p xml:id="auto_y4rgbjgr">
                            If the student and the toy car are moving in the same direction, 
                            the relative speed is given as;
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_venhizex">
                            Relative speed = Speed of Toy Car + Speed of Student
                    
                        </p>
                    </li>

                     <li xml:id="auto_sx8lhdir">
                        <p xml:id="auto_6rq2ss9e">
                            Discuss;
                            <ol xml:id="auto_6ecczw5b" marker="(i).">
                                <li xml:id="auto_rvrkjynd">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_hlk2jy9m">
                                        Who moved faster? Was the student walking faster or slower than the toy car?
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_fwyy6i9m">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_asohn5x2">
                                        Why one object might have moved faster than the other. 
                                        Did the toy car move faster because it was pulled, or was the student faster in their walking?
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_6s8fd4vj">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_ps8jztks">
                                        The relative speed: How does the speed of each participant relate to the other? 
                                        Did they move away from each other, or did they move closer together?
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li xml:id="auto_8axzq49n">
                        <p xml:id="auto_2lylnyct">
                            Now try the activity in different conditions or compare vraious speed by repeating the race multiple times.
                            <ul xml:id="auto_uqri1aqn">
                                <li xml:id="auto_6rezfwiu">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_ifbyo6x4">
                                        Have the student walk faster or slower.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_ucvu1egz">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_87e0grk5">
                                        Change the length of the race to see how it affects the results.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_5yktkzwg">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_gipx0lom">
                                        Adjust how fast the toy car is pulled.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </activity>

   <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction (10 minutes)</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_y2jh241q">
                After students have explored through the anchor activity, formalise their discoveries with the key concepts in the textbook.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_jjzicebq">
                <alert>Teaching Tips:</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_jz74nfcn">
                <ul>
                    <li xml:id="auto_yfctmn64">Create a clear comparison table on the board: Same Direction (subtract) vs Different Directions (add).</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_x720dppp">Common misconception: students may confuse which formula to use. Reinforce with visual arrows: same direction → subtract, opposite direction → add.</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_mbp773lh">Emphasise that problems with different departure times require calculating the distance already covered before applying relative speed.</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_cj0ze9ep">Ask: <q>Why do objects moving toward each other meet faster than objects moving in the same direction?</q></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </axiom>
        <exploration xml:id="exploration-relative-speed-opposite-direction">
            <title>Relative Speeds in Opposite Directions</title>


            <introduction xml:id="auto_6oed9p4g">
                <p xml:id="auto_waj7lzu0">
                    In this activity, you will explore what happens when two objects move <em>toward each other</em>. 
                    When objects travel in opposite directions, the distance between them decreases more quickly 
                    because their speeds combine. Before starting, review the 
                    <xref ref="instructions-relative-speed-opposite" text="custom">instructions below</xref> 
                    for using the simulation.
                </p>
            </introduction>

            <figure xml:id="fig-relative-speed-opposite-three-panel">
                <caption>3-Panel Interactive: Opposite Direction Relative Speed Simulation</caption>

                <interactive xml:id="interactive-relative-speed-opposite"
                    platform="jsxgraph"
                    width="90%"
                    aspect="1:1"
                    source="jsxgraph/relative-speeds-opposite.js">

                    <sidebyside width="85%" margins="5%">
                        <stack>
                            <slate xml:id="box_controls_opposite" surface="jsxboard" aspect="6:1"/>
                            <slate xml:id="box_road_opposite" surface="jsxboard" aspect="6:3"/>
                            <slate xml:id="box_actions_opposite" surface="jsxboard" aspect="6:1"/>
                        </stack>
                    </sidebyside>
                    <instructions xml:id="instructions-relative-speed-opposite">
                        <p xml:id="auto_pg4v54uq">
                            <ol>
                                <li xml:id="auto_nu69piba">Drag the red and blue points on the axis in the middle panel to set the starting positions of the two objects.</li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_2ijc4cpo">Use the sliders in the top panel to set the speeds of Object A (Red) and Object B (Blue).</li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_xubh929l">Click <c>Start</c> in the bottom panel to begin the animation.</li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_mr4byt7z">Watch the dotted lines and the labels above each car to see how far each object has traveled.</li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_896oic7e">If the cars meet, the simulation will pause automatically and display the message <q>Cars Met!</q>.</li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_pxq9yud3">Click <c>Resume</c> to allow the cars to continue moving past each other.</li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_015uvkjb">You may click <c>Pause</c> at any time to stop the animation and observe the positions of the cars.</li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_xhztso2k">Click <c>Reset</c> to stop the simulation and return the cars and timer to their starting state so that you can run a new experiment.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>

                        <p xml:id="auto_ddk1cztb">
                            Use the interactive to investigate the following situations:
                            <ol>
                                <li xml:id="auto_rld8841d">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_wv3ihk82">
                                        Set both objects to moderate speeds (for example, <m>5</m> m/s each). Start the animation. 
                                        Observe how quickly the cars approach each other. Why does the relative speed equal the sum of their speeds?
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li xml:id="auto_fjjkn2zb">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_4lfod2di">
                                        Increase the speed of one object while keeping the other constant. 
                                        Pause the simulation before the cars meet and estimate how long it will take for them to collide. 
                                        Then resume the animation to test your prediction.
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li xml:id="auto_3jqdwaaw">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_jamt3sur">
                                        Drag the cars very far apart before starting the animation. 
                                        How does increasing the starting distance affect the meeting time?
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li xml:id="auto_dge06qr9">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_ed0neu14">
                                        After the cars meet, click <q>Resume</q> and observe how they continue moving away from each other. 
                                        What happens to the distance between them after they pass?
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </instructions>

                </interactive>
            </figure>
        </exploration>
        <insight xml:id="auto_q50t6emd">
            <p xml:id="auto_u3hhwqlu">
                <alert>Definition:</alert>
                When two objects move toward each other (in different directions), their
                relative speed is the sum of their individual speeds.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_bo70n8h8">
                <alert>Formula for Different Directions:</alert>
                When two bodies move toward each other, their relative
                speed is the sum of the individual speeds.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_sybmfhil">
                <alert>Relative Speed = Speed of Object <m>1 +</m> Speed of Object <m>2</m></alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_9rf7dlbv">
                <alert>Why Add Speeds?</alert>
                When objects move toward each other, they close the gap between them
                faster than if only one were moving. The combined effect is captured by adding their speeds.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_b991jfpp">
               <alert>Time to Meet:</alert> 
               <m>\text{Time} = \frac{\text{Distance}}{\text{Relative Speed}}</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_44t7juzt">
               <alert>Key Insight:</alert> 
               Objects moving toward each other will meet faster than objects moving in the
                same direction.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_kz5rtm6z">
                <alert>Comparison:</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_a6q8edtc">
                Same direction: Relative Speed = Faster Speed - Slower Speed
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_e9nmu9n1">
                Different directions (toward each other): Relative Speed = Speed 1 + Speed 2
            </p>
        </insight>

        <!-- <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction (10 minutes)</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_4igrhok0">
                After students have explored through the anchor activity, formalise their discoveries with the key concepts in the textbook.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_x6bmifyu">
                <alert>Teaching Tips:</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_b89rcfs1">
                <ul>
                    <li xml:id="auto_j2yz0yt1">Create a clear comparison table on the board: Same Direction (subtract) vs Different Directions (add).</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_fq9xi402">Common misconception: students may confuse which formula to use. Reinforce with visual arrows: same direction → subtract, opposite direction → add.</li>
