        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application (10 minutes)</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_97ubrtc4">
                Guide students through the worked examples below.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_sx2hd5vn">
                <alert>Teaching Tips:</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_xumm1a8i">
                <ul>
                    <li xml:id="auto_snnvfg3w">For the first example (trains from X and Y), carefully walk through the staggered departure times — this is a common source of error.</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_h3m47zu7">Emphasise the step: <q>First, calculate how far the first train has already travelled before the second departs.</q></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_u6nziwle">For the second example (cyclists in opposite directions), note that the verification step is important — total distance should match the given separation.</li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </axiom>

        <example xml:id="auto_kouuxr7u">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_opv4mn6x">
                    A train left town X at <m>10:00</m> <em>AM</em> and traveled towards town 
                    <m>Y</m> at a speed of <m>90</m> <em>km/h</em>. 
                    A second train left town <m>Y</m> at <m>11:00</m> <em>AM</em> and traveled towards town 
                    <m>X</m> at <m>120</m> <em>km/h</em>. 
                    The distance between town <m>X</m> and town <m>Y</m> is <m>360</m> <m>km</m>.
                    <ol xml:id="auto_ddtfxjqk" marker="(i).">
                        <li xml:id="auto_l6q6l3k1">
                            <p xml:id="auto_n64espqt">
                                At what time will the two trains meet?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_ia3wm5eu">
                            <p xml:id="auto_63klf9v5">
                                How far from town X will they meet?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_66ohvp5g">
                    The first train departs at <m>10:00</m> <em>AM</em>, 
                    and the second train departs at <m>11:00</m> <em>AM</em>. 
                    Therefore, the first train travels for <m>1</m> hour before the second train starts.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_nu7qavj4">
                    The distance traveled by the first train in 1 hour:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Distance} \amp = 90 \, km/h \times \ \, hour </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_2htax4sb">
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \amp = 90 \, km </mrow>
                    </md>
                    Thus, by <m>11:00</m> <em>AM</em>, the remaining distance between the two trains is:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>360\, km \, - \, 90\,km \amp = 270\,km</mrow>
                    </md>
                    The time it takes for the two trains to meet after 11:00 AM is given by the formula:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Time} \amp = \frac{\text{Distnace}}{\text{Relative Speed}} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_dvaoq3dn">
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \amp = \frac{270\,km}{210\,km/h} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_4gi7sdez">
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \amp = 1.2857\,hours </mrow>
                    </md>
                    This is approximately <m>1</m> hr and <m>17</m> minutes.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_dfq5t8md">
                    Therefore, the trains will meet at:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>11:00 \text{AM} + \text{1 hour and 17 minutes} \amp = 12:17 \text{PM} </mrow>
                    </md>
                    So the two trains meet at <m>12:17 \text{PM}</m>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_mf08z57v">
                    The distance traveled by the first train before the meeting is:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Distance} \amp = 90\,km/h \times 1.2857\, hours </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_n8r0skzq">
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \amp = 115.714 \, km </mrow>
                    </md>
                    Thus, the meeting point is approximately <m>116\,km </m> from town <m>X.</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="auto_j0znajpe">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_bnhhgm2k">
                    Two cyclists start from the same point and travel in opposite directions. 
                    One cyclist rides at 20 km/h, and the other rides at 30 km/h. After 2 hours, 
                    they are 100 km apart.
                    <ol xml:id="auto_kdqdse8q" marker="(a).">
                        <li xml:id="auto_335r5kk7">
                            <p xml:id="auto_80xz4kc0">
                                How long did it take for the cyclists to be 100 km apart?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_br5hhhnu">
                            <p xml:id="auto_af5c0nxp">
                                How far did each cyclist travel?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_x42xlr3j">
                    The cyclists are moving in opposite directions. 
                    The total distance between them after <m>2</m> hours is <m>100</m> <em>km</em>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_0mpd3p2b">
                    Since the cyclists are moving in opposite directions, 
                    their relative speed is the sum of their individual speeds:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Relative speed} \amp = 20\,km/h + 30\,km/h. </mrow>
                    </md>
                    In 2 hours, the total distance traveled by both cyclists is:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Total distance} \amp = 50\,km/h \times 2\,hours </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_qz84rerd">
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \amp = 100\,km </mrow>
                    </md>
                    So, the cyclists will be 100 km apart after 2 hours. This confirms the given information.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_c5wayd6z">
                    The first cyclist, riding at 20 km/h, travels:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Distance covered by first cyclist} \amp = 20\,km/h \times 2\,hours </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_37j2r4s9">
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \amp = 40\,km. </mrow>
                    </md>
                    The second cyclist, riding at 30 km/h, travels:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Distance covered by second cyclist} \amp = 30\,km/h \times 2\,hours </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        
            <exercise  label="ex-finding-the-time-and-distance-covered-by-two-motorist-travelling">
                <stack label="stk-finding-the-time-and-distance-covered-by-two-motorist-travelling" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-9-Linear-Motion/Relative-speed-When-Objects-Move-Toward-Each-Other-(Opposite-Dir/Finding-the-time-and-distance-covered-by-two-motorist-travelling.xml" />
            </exercise>
            
    <exercise xml:id="ex-finding-speeds-of-two-people-cycling-toward-each-other-from-two-">
        <stack label="stk-finding-speeds-of-two-people-cycling-toward-each-other-from-two-" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-9-Linear-Motion/Relative-speed-When-Objects-Move-Toward-Each-Other-(Opposite-Dir/Finding-speeds-of-two-people-cycling-toward-each-other-from-two-.xml"/>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-finding-the-time-two-cyclist-travelling-towards-each-other-met">
        <stack label="stk-finding-the-time-two-cyclist-travelling-towards-each-other-met" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-9-Linear-Motion/Relative-speed-When-Objects-Move-Toward-Each-Other-(Opposite-Dir/Finding-the-time-two-cyclist-travelling-towards-each-other-met.xml"/>
    </exercise>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 4: Assessment — Exit Ticket (5 minutes)</title>
              <li xml:id="auto_ju25dpel">
                <title><alert>Exit Ticket</alert></title>
                   <p xml:id="auto_8hqkpaa9">
                    Learners independently complete a short assessment task (select from the exercises below).
